Note:
PHYSICAL_CONSTANTS - SI-exact and measured physical constants

This module exposes the seven defining constants of the SI system (2019
redefinition) plus the most commonly used measured constants. Each is
exposed both as a plain Float (Float64 SI base value) and as a Quantity
with the proper dimension - the Quantity form is more expressive but
slower because it allocates and stamps the dimension.

The 2019 SI redefinition (BIPM, CGPM 26th conf., November 2018) makes
seven physical constants EXACT by definition. These are:

  delta_nu_Cs   - Cs-133 hyperfine transition frequency = 9192631770 Hz
  c             - speed of light in vacuum               = 299792458 m/s
  h             - Planck constant                        = 6.62607015e-34 J*s
  e             - elementary charge                      = 1.602176634e-19 C
  k             - Boltzmann constant                     = 1.380649e-23 J/K
  N_A           - Avogadro constant                      = 6.02214076e23 mol^-1
  K_cd          - luminous efficacy of monochromatic
                  radiation of frequency 540*10^12 Hz   = 683 lm/W

DERIVED EXACT (from the seven above):
  hbar          - reduced Planck constant h / (2*pi)
  R             - molar gas constant N_A * k
  F             - Faraday constant N_A * e

MEASURED (CODATA 2018 values):
  G             - gravitational constant
  g_n           - standard acceleration of free fall (defined value 9.80665)
  m_e           - electron mass
  m_p           - proton mass
  m_n           - neutron mass
  alpha         - fine-structure constant
  R_inf         - Rydberg constant
  epsilon_0     - vacuum permittivity (derived from alpha, e, h, c)
  mu_0          - vacuum permeability  (derived from alpha, e, h, c)
  Z_0           - characteristic impedance of vacuum

CITATIONS

  - BIPM, "The International System of Units (SI)", 9th ed., 2019.
  - CGPM (2018), Resolution 1: "On the revision of the International
    System of Units (SI)". 26th meeting of the CGPM.
  - Mohr, Newell, Taylor (2016): "CODATA Recommended Values of the
    Fundamental Physical Constants: 2014", RMP 88, 035009.
  - Tiesinga, Mohr, Newell, Taylor (2021): "CODATA Recommended Values
    of the Fundamental Physical Constants: 2018", RMP 93, 025010.
  - Mills, I. M., et al. (2006): "Redefinition of the kilogram, ampere,
    kelvin and mole: a proposed approach to implementing CIPM
    recommendation 1 (CI-2005)", Metrologia 43, 227.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/units/dimension.runa" as Dim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/units/unit.runa" as Unit
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/units/quantity.runa" as Q

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - SI defining exact constants (Float form)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "speed_of_light_c_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Speed of light in vacuum. Defined to be EXACTLY 299792458 m/s
        as part of the SI 2019 redefinition. This value is the basis
        for the SI definition of the metre.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Float literal storing the exact integer value.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 299792458.0
End Process

Process called "planck_h_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Planck constant. Defined as 6.62607015 times ten to the negative
        thirty-fourth power J s as part of the SI 2019 redefinition.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Stage1 lexer accepts e+N but not e-N; express via division.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mantissa be 6.62607015
    Let scale be 1.0e34
    Return mantissa divided by scale
End Process

Process called "elementary_charge_e_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Elementary charge. Defined to be EXACTLY 1.602176634e-19 C as
        part of the SI 2019 redefinition.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Float literal via division to encode the negative exponent.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mantissa be 1.602176634
    Let scale be 1.0e19
    Return mantissa divided by scale
End Process

Process called "boltzmann_k_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Boltzmann constant. Defined to be EXACTLY 1.380649e-23 J/K as
        part of the SI 2019 redefinition.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Float literal via division.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mantissa be 1.380649
    Let scale be 1.0e23
    Return mantissa divided by scale
End Process

Process called "avogadro_N_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Avogadro constant. Defined to be EXACTLY 6.02214076e23 mol^-1
        as part of the SI 2019 redefinition.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct Float literal.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let v be 6.02214076e23
    Return v
End Process

Process called "cesium_hyperfine_freq_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Cesium-133 ground-state hyperfine transition frequency. Defined
        to be EXACTLY 9192631770 Hz as part of the SI 2019 redefinition.
        Basis for the SI definition of the second.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct Float literal.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 9192631770.0
End Process

Process called "luminous_efficacy_Kcd_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Luminous efficacy of monochromatic radiation of frequency
        540 THz. Defined to be EXACTLY 683 lm/W as part of the SI 2019
        redefinition. Basis for the SI definition of the candela.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct Float literal.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 683.0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - Derived from the defining seven
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "hbar_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Reduced Planck constant: h / (2 * pi).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Computed at runtime from the exact h and the high-precision
        approximation of 2*pi. Pi is given to ~ 1e-16 precision so the
        derived constant carries the same precision floor.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One Float divide. ~ 20 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let two_pi be 6.283185307179586
    Return (proc planck_h_si) divided by two_pi
End Process

Process called "molar_gas_constant_R_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Molar gas constant: R = N_A * k. By the SI 2019 redefinition this
        product is exact: R = 6.02214076e23 * 1.380649e-23 J/(K*mol).
        Computing the product at runtime introduces at most one ULP error.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Product of two exact defining constants.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One Float multiply.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return (proc avogadro_N_si) multiplied by (proc boltzmann_k_si)
End Process

Process called "faraday_F_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Faraday constant: F = N_A * e.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Product of two exact defining constants.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One Float multiply.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return (proc avogadro_N_si) multiplied by (proc elementary_charge_e_si)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Measured constants (CODATA 2018)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "gravitational_G_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Newtonian constant of gravitation. CODATA 2018 recommended value
        is 6.67430e-11 m^3 / (kg * s^2). The relative standard uncertainty
        is 2.2e-5, which is large by physics-constant standards because
        gravity is so weak that laboratory measurements are difficult.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Float literal via division for the negative exponent.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. The 2.2e-5 relative uncertainty means callers using G
        in critical computations should propagate uncertainty.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mantissa be 6.67430
    Let scale be 1.0e11
    Return mantissa divided by scale
End Process

Process called "standard_gravity_g_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Standard acceleration of free fall. Defined to be EXACTLY
        9.80665 m/s^2 by the 3rd General Conference on Weights and
        Measures (1901). This is the conventional value used for
        engineering conversions (e.g. weight = mass * g_n).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct Float literal.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 9.80665
End Process

Process called "electron_mass_me_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Electron rest mass. CODATA 2018 value 9.1093837015e-31 kg.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Float literal via division.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mantissa be 9.1093837015
    Let scale be 1.0e31
    Return mantissa divided by scale
End Process

Process called "proton_mass_mp_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Proton rest mass. CODATA 2018 value 1.67262192369e-27 kg.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Float literal via division.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mantissa be 1.67262192369
    Let scale be 1.0e27
    Return mantissa divided by scale
End Process

Process called "neutron_mass_mn_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Neutron rest mass. CODATA 2018 value 1.67492749804e-27 kg.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Float literal via division.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mantissa be 1.67492749804
    Let scale be 1.0e27
    Return mantissa divided by scale
End Process

Process called "fine_structure_alpha_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Fine-structure constant. Dimensionless. CODATA 2018 value
        0.0072973525693, relative uncertainty 1.5e-10.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct Float literal.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 0.0072973525693
End Process

Process called "rydberg_Rinf_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Rydberg constant. CODATA 2018 value 10973731.568160 m^-1.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Direct Float literal.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return 10973731.568160
End Process

Process called "vacuum_permittivity_epsilon0_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Electric constant (vacuum permittivity). Since the 2019 SI
        redefinition, epsilon_0 is no longer exact (the ampere is no
        longer defined via mu_0). CODATA 2018 value 8.8541878128e-12 F/m.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Float literal via division.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mantissa be 8.8541878128
    Let scale be 1.0e12
    Return mantissa divided by scale
End Process

Process called "vacuum_permeability_mu0_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Magnetic constant (vacuum permeability). Post-2019 SI value
        1.25663706212e-6 N/A^2. Computed CODATA 2018 value.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Float literal via division.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Compile-time constant.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mantissa be 1.25663706212
    Let scale be 1.0e6
    Return mantissa divided by scale
End Process

Process called "vacuum_impedance_Z0_si" returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Characteristic impedance of vacuum: Z_0 = mu_0 * c.
        Approximately 376.730313668 ohms.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Product of mu_0 and c.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One float multiply.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return (proc vacuum_permeability_mu0_si) multiplied by (proc speed_of_light_c_si)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - Quantity-typed accessors
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Each defining or measured constant is exposed as a Quantity with
Note: the appropriate dimension, suitable for direct use in dimensional
Note: arithmetic.

Process called "speed_of_light_c_quantity" returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Wrap the speed of light as a Quantity with dimension m/s and
        unit-tag composite (no named SI symbol for the velocity unit).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        quantity_create_from_components with dim_create(1,0,-1,0,0,0,0).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Three field writes plus the dim_create. ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dim be proc dim_create from Dim with 1, 0, 0 minus 1, 0, 0, 0, 0
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components from Q with (proc speed_of_light_c_si), dim, (proc unit_tag_composite from Unit)
End Process

Process called "planck_h_quantity" returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Planck constant as a Quantity with dimension J*s = m^2*kg/s.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Build dimension vector (2, 1, -1, 0, 0, 0, 0).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dim be proc dim_create from Dim with 2, 1, 0 minus 1, 0, 0, 0, 0
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components from Q with (proc planck_h_si), dim, (proc unit_tag_composite from Unit)
End Process

Process called "elementary_charge_e_quantity" returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Elementary charge as a Quantity with the coulomb tag.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Use the unit_tag_coulomb so quantity_to_string renders "C".
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 15 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return proc quantity_create_si from Q with (proc elementary_charge_e_si), (proc unit_tag_coulomb from Unit)
End Process

Process called "boltzmann_k_quantity" returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Boltzmann constant as a Quantity with dimension J/K.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Dimension vector (2, 1, -2, 0, -1, 0, 0).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dim be proc dim_create from Dim with 2, 1, 0 minus 2, 0, 0 minus 1, 0, 0
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components from Q with (proc boltzmann_k_si), dim, (proc unit_tag_composite from Unit)
End Process

Process called "avogadro_N_quantity" returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Avogadro constant as a Quantity with dimension mol^-1.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Dimension vector (0, 0, 0, 0, 0, -1, 0).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dim be proc dim_create from Dim with 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0 minus 1, 0
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components from Q with (proc avogadro_N_si), dim, (proc unit_tag_composite from Unit)
End Process

Process called "cesium_hyperfine_freq_quantity" returns Quantity:
    Return proc quantity_create_si from Q with (proc cesium_hyperfine_freq_si), (proc unit_tag_hertz from Unit)
End Process

Process called "luminous_efficacy_Kcd_quantity" returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Luminous efficacy K_cd as a Quantity with dimension lm/W. Since
        lm = cd and W has dimension (2,1,-3,0,0,0,0), K_cd's dimension
        vector is (-2, -1, 3, 0, 0, 0, 1).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        dim_create with the computed exponents.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dim be proc dim_create from Dim with 0 minus 2, 0 minus 1, 3, 0, 0, 0, 1
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components from Q with (proc luminous_efficacy_Kcd_si), dim, (proc unit_tag_composite from Unit)
End Process

Process called "gravitational_G_quantity" returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Newton's gravitational constant as a Quantity. Dimension
        m^3 / (kg * s^2) = (3, -1, -2, 0, 0, 0, 0).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        dim_create with the computed exponents.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dim be proc dim_create from Dim with 3, 0 minus 1, 0 minus 2, 0, 0, 0, 0
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components from Q with (proc gravitational_G_si), dim, (proc unit_tag_composite from Unit)
End Process

Process called "standard_gravity_g_quantity" returns Quantity:
    @Reasoning:
        Standard gravity 9.80665 m/s^2 as a Quantity with the acceleration
        dimension (1, 0, -2, 0, 0, 0, 0).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        dim_create + quantity_create_from_components.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 30 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let dim be proc dim_create from Dim with 1, 0, 0 minus 2, 0, 0, 0, 0
    Return proc quantity_create_from_components from Q with (proc standard_gravity_g_si), dim, (proc unit_tag_composite from Unit)
End Process

Process called "electron_mass_me_quantity" returns Quantity:
    Return proc quantity_create_si from Q with (proc electron_mass_me_si), (proc unit_tag_kilogram from Unit)
End Process

Process called "proton_mass_mp_quantity" returns Quantity:
    Return proc quantity_create_si from Q with (proc proton_mass_mp_si), (proc unit_tag_kilogram from Unit)
End Process

Process called "neutron_mass_mn_quantity" returns Quantity:
    Return proc quantity_create_si from Q with (proc neutron_mass_mn_si), (proc unit_tag_kilogram from Unit)
End Process
